1. Introduction

The data used in the following analysis has been taken from the US Census Bureau, American Community Survey for 5 year periods. It is based on the tables described below. All the tables have been directly imported into R through Tidycensus – | ACS Table | Variables | Label | Description | |———–|————————–|———-|——————————————————–| | B01001 | B01001_001E | Pop | Total Population | | B02001 | B02001_002E | White | Count of White Population | | B02001 | B02001_003E | Black | Count of Black Population | | B02001 | B02001_004E | AIAN | Count of American Indian and Alaskan Native Population | | B02001 | B02001_005E | Asian | Count of Asian Population | | B02001 | B02001_001E, B02001_002E | Nonwhite | Count of Nonwhite Population | | B03001 | B03001_003E | Latino | Count of Latino Population | | B19013 | B19013_001E | MHHI | Median Household Income |

1.1. Chicago Metropolitan Region

The primary aim of this analysis is to understand how households are segregated in the Chicago Metropolitan Region, spanning the following counties | County | FIPS | |———|——| | Cook | 031 | | DeKalb | 037 | | DuPage | 043 | | Grundy | 063 | | Kane | 089 | | Kendall | 093 | | Lake | 097 | | McHenry | 111 | | Will | 197 | Several tracts within the aforementioned counties are uninhabited and are therefore removed from the analysis of housing segregation described below.
